:::summary
Martin Luther (1483–1546) was a German monk, theologian, and reformer whose posting of the Ninety-Five Theses in 1517 sparked the Protestant Reformation — one of the most consequential events in the history of Christianity. His doctrine of justification by faith alone transformed Western Christianity and, from a Latter-day Saint perspective, was a providential step in preparing the world for the eventual Restoration of the gospel.
:::

